On Tue, Jun 09, 1998 at 04:29:25PM +0900, Masataka Ohta wrote:
> As IANA today is not a US-local corporation and under the full
                                                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
> control of ISOC, not USG, it's fine for IAHC leave root zone
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
> authority to IANA.

This is incorrect, and this incorrect assumption has been an almost
fatal oversight on the part of IAHC and many others.  It is an error I
labored under for some time, as well, because many of the
relationships are not public, and Jon Postel does not talk about 
them.  The cold fact is that the USG actually does have a certain 
amount of control over IANA, control that Jon recognizes; and 
ISOC/IETF's control is nowhere near as strong as you imagine it to 
be.  This is an unfortunate reality, one I learned with some 
difficulty.  It is also not a reality I take a public position on, as 
you might imagine, so I would appreciate it if you keep this private.

Here is a quote from a paper written by Jon Postel in
January, 1998:

    The IANA function was originally performed at UCLA and (skipping
    some intermediate steps) subsequently expanded over time at the
    Information Sciences Institute (ISI) of the University of Southern
    California (USC).  It was established under DARPA funding and it
    has continued to be supported under the US Government's aegis
    since its inception.  This had proven to be a satisfactory
    arrangement until recently.  Currently, however, there are
    enormous pressures to evolve the IANA into an organization based
    on industry self-governance and support.  The US Government has
    indicated to ISI that it is time to make the transition and that
    it will not continue financial support after September 1998, in
    the interest of encouraging self-governance based on industry
    support. 

Furthermore, Jon Postel considers himself primarily a network
researcher, and IANA is a side issue for him.  The USG apparently
controls a considerable percentage of his research funding, so they
have leverage over him in that regard.  Plus, there are indications
that he has ambivalent feelings about how the IAHC conducted itself,
as well. 

There are a number of other factors, as well: 1) The USG does not
speak with a single voice -- the Department of Justice and the
Department of Commerce have fought over this issue, and the US
Congress is an unpredictable wild card; 2) SAIC, the parent
corporation of NSI, is incredibly powerful in Washington (you have
surely seen the "Raiders of the Lost Arc" story --
http://songbird.com/pab/raiders); 3) Magaziner is a policy cripple,
and has other problems, as well (see
http://dolphin.gulf.net/jan02/Magaziner -- he has many enemies in
Washington, as well, and Gore is not happy with him); 4) Gore's 
political ambitions play a big role; 5) very important: the root 
servers are a convention, and the alternate root movement would gain 
many many converts if the USG was too blatant.

In fact this has all been an incredibly complex and delicate balancing
act, and for me a profound lesson in political reality.  Given all 
this, the WP is a real victory for us.  

The most important aspect is that it puts NSI firmly under the control
of IANA, incidentally, and NSI, despite their press release, is not at
all happy about it.  In fact, 1) they are trying to hijack the
formation of the new IANA corporation; and 2) they have talked another
congressman into holding hearings next week, and have totally stacked
the witness list in their favor.  I don't think these efforts will
succeed, but NSI is a determined and powerful enemy. 

Please note that this is a private message.

