> 
> The WP is fine, because it can be safely ignored.

No, it cannot.  It states that the USG will enter into "an agreement" 
with the new IANA.  That agreement is necessary, because the only 
control over NSI is the USG.

> > The most important aspect is that it puts NSI firmly under the control
> > of IANA, incidentally, and NSI, despite their press release, is not at
> > all happy about it.  In fact, 1) they are trying to hijack the
> > formation of the new IANA corporation; and 2) they have talked another
> > congressman into holding hearings next week, and have totally stacked
> > the witness list in their favor.  I don't think these efforts will
> > succeed, but NSI is a determined and powerful enemy. 
> 
> NSI or US-local congress is a problem only when you let USG control
> DNS.

What a nice, simplistic view you have.  The fact is that NSI has 
claimed ownership of the database that contains the .com/.net/.org
registrations.  If they make that claim stick, then they have control 
over the vast majority of the DNS registrations.  NSI has a contract 
with the USG, and that contract is the only realistic lever that can 
be used to pry that database from NSI.  If that database is not 
removed from NSI's control, then the actions of IANA are moot -- NSI 
will simply run the root servers in fact, and IANA will be ignored.

> > Please note that this is a private message.
> 
